symbolic links (also known as “soft links” or “symlinks”): Refer to a symbolic path indicating the abstract location of another file.

hard links : Refer to the specific location of physical data. Same INODE.


Symbolic link.

$ ln -s target_file1 link1

then we call link1 it's redirect to target_file
eg.
$ bash
bash -> /bin/sh
bash is link, and /bin/sh is target


Symlinks To a Directory.

$ ln -s /mnt/my_drive/movies ~/my_movies

Overwrite link.

$ ln -sf file1 link1

Removing Symlinks.

rm

OR

unlink link1
